{"id":"1807.06226","submitter":"Jiyeon Lee","authors":"S. N. Ethier and Jiyeon Lee","title":"The tilted flashing Brownian ratchet","comments":"21 pages, 5 figures. arXiv admin note: text overlap with\n  arXiv:1710.05295","journal-ref":"Fluctuation and Noise Letters 18 (2019) 1950005","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The flashing Brownian ratchet is a stochastic process that alternates between\ntwo regimes, a one-dimensional Brownian motion and a Brownian ratchet, the\nlatter being a one-dimensional diffusion process that drifts towards a minimum\nof a periodic asymmetric sawtooth potential. The result is directed motion. In\nthe presence of a static homogeneous force that acts in the direction opposite\nthat of the directed motion, there is a reduction (or even a reversal) of the\ndirected motion effect. Such a process may be called a tilted flashing Brownian\nratchet. We show how one can study this process numerically, using a random\nwalk approximation or, equivalently, using numerical solution of the\nFokker-Planck equation. Stochastic simulation is another viable method.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Jul 2018 05:13:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 24 Jan 2019 09:13:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-02-07"}
