{"id":"1807.06293","submitter":"Gilles Tarjus","authors":"G. Biroli, C. Cammarota, G. Tarjus, and M. Tarzia","title":"Random-Field Ising like effective theory of the glass transition: I\n  Mean-Field Models","comments":"18 pages (+ 12 pages of appendices), 5 figures. Followed by companion\n  paper II","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 98, 174205 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.98.174205","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.soft","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper and in the companion one we address the problem of identifying\nthe effective theory that describes the statistics of the fluctuations of what\nis thought to be the relevant order parameter for glassy systems---the overlap\nfield with an equilibrium reference configuration---close to the putative\nthermodynamic glass transition. Our starting point is the mean-field theory of\nglass formation which relies on the existence of a complex free-energy\nlandscape with a multitude of metastable states. In this paper, we focus on\narchetypal mean-field models possessing this type of free-energy landscape and\nset up the framework to determine the exact effective theory. We show that the\neffective theory at the mean-field level is generically of the random-field +\nrandom-bond Ising type. We also discuss what are the main issues concerning the\nextension of our result to finite-dimensional systems. This extension is\naddressed in detail in the companion paper.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Jul 2018 09:31:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-11-21"}
